A polyfill is a piece of code (usually JavaScript on the Web) used to provide modern functionality on older browsers that do not natively support it.
For example, a polyfill could be used to mimic the functionality of an HTML Canvas element on Microsoft Internet Explorer 7 using a Silverlight plugin, or mimic support for CSS rem units, or text-shadow, or other things that were introduced only on newer browsers.
" A polyfill is a shim for a browser API ," according to the definition. Rather than a proprietary API, you're most likely to encounter polyfills that allow you to use modern HTML5 or CSS browser APIs in older browsers that don't support them natively.
The HTML5 Cross Browser Polyfills wiki page contains a fairly comprehensive list of polyfills for a variety of HTML5 technologies. Here are some examples of polyfills:
es5-shim.js - ECMAScript 5 API support for older browsers

The term broadcasting describes how numpy treats arrays with different shapes during arithmetic operations. Subject to certain constraints, the smaller array is “broadcast” across the larger array so that they have compatible shapes. Broadcasting provides a means of vectorizing array operations so that looping occurs in C instead of Python. It does this without making needless copies of data and usually leads to efficient algorithm implementations. There are, however, cases where broadcasting is a bad idea because it leads to inefficient use of memory that slows computation.
NumPy operations are usually done on pairs of arrays on an element-by-element basis. In the simplest case, the two arrays must have exactly the same shape, as in the following example:
>>> a = np.array([1.0, 2.0, 3.0])
>>> b = np.array([2.0, 2.0, 2.0])
>>> a * b
array([ 2.,  4.,  6.])
NumPy’s broadcasting rule relaxes this

The brute force solution is to iterate over all sub-arrays and check the sum of each one. This is O(n^2) time, which is not ideal.
A better solution is to use a sliding window approach. We start with a window of size 1 and keep track of the sum of the elements in the window. If the sum is less than or equal to k, we increase the size of the window by 1. If the sum is greater than k, we decrease the size of the window by 1. We keep doing this until we reach the end of the array.
This solution is O(n) time, which is much better than the brute force solution.

    max_len = 0
    for i in range(len(a)):
        while j < len(a) and sum + a[j] <= k:
            sum += a[j]
        max_len = max(max_len, j - i)
        sum -= a[i]
    return max_len

Swapping is a memory management scheme in which any process can be temporarily swapped from main memory to secondary memory so that the main memory can be made available for other processes. Semantic search is a search or a question or an action that produces meaningful results, even when the retrieved items contain none of the query terms, or the search involves no query text at all.
For example, when you search for “How to bake a cake” on Google, it shows you a card with video instructions from YouTube, even though there is no word “video” in the query. Or when you search for “completely unrelated pictures”, it shows you a funny picture of a group of random things lined up in a row.
Semantic search seeks to improve search accuracy by understanding searcher intent and the contextual meaning of terms as they appear in the searchable dataspace, whether on the Web or within a closed system, to generate more relevant results. Semantic search systems consider various points including context of search, location, intent, variation of words, synonyms, generalized and specialized queries, concept matching and natural language queries to provide relevant search results. Major web search engines like Google and Bing incorporate some elements of semantic search.

The project management processes are usually presented as discrete processes with defined interfaces while, in practice, they overlap and interact in ways that cannot be completely detailed in the PMBOK® Guide. The specific projects will dictate how much iteration and overlap will occur between the various project management processes. These integrative actions can be most effectively addressed by a project management process that starts early in the project, includes a project charter, a project management plan, and a project scope statement, and integrates and coordinates the various project management activities from initiation through project closure. The integrative nature of projects and project management can be better understood if we think of the other activities performed when we perform the work associated with the various project management processes. For example, we perform a project management process (scope definition) that produces a scope statement. We perform another project management process (schedule development) that produces a project schedule. The additional processes used to perform these processes are not documented because they are generic to all projects. The integrative nature of project management requires the Monitoring and Controlling Process Group interaction with every aspect of the other Process Groups. In addition, since integration is a key responsibility of the project manager, the nature of the project manager’s role on a project is discussed in this chapter. Zero-knowledge proofs are a cryptographic technique that can prove something to be true to someone without having to reveal the information itself.
This is useful in a lot of situations, for example, proving you know a password without having to give it to someone in plain text.
In this article, I’ll go over how zero-knowledge proofs work using a simple example.
The example is based on the paper “How to Explain Zero-Knowledge Protocols to Your Children” by Jean-Jacques Quisquater et al.
The paper was published in 1989, but still provides a great explanation of how zero-knowledge proofs work.

The cave can be opened by saying the magic words “open sesame”.

The solution is to use a zero-knowledge proof.
The proof works as follows:Ali Baba’s wife goes to entrance A and Ali Baba goes to entrance B.
Ali Baba’s wife chooses a random direction to go in, either left or right.
Ali Baba’s wife goes in the chosen direction and Ali Baba goes in the opposite direction.
If Ali Baba’s wife reaches the door, she opens it and goes through.
If Ali Baba reaches the door, he waits for Ali Baba’s wife to open it.
If Ali Baba’s wife does not reach the door, she goes back to entrance A and Ali Baba goes back to entrance B.
The process is repeated until Ali Baba’s wife reaches the door and opens it.
The proof is complete when Ali Baba’s wife reaches the door and opens it.
The proof is zero-knowledge because Ali Baba does not learn the magic words.
He only learns that Ali Baba’s wife knows the magic words.
The proof is also interactive because Ali Baba’s wife needs to interact with Ali Baba to complete the proof.
